item.title: Allegations against Al Fayed didn't come as 'biggest surprise': former manager says staff aware about owner’s interest in ‘young, blond girls'
item.description: Gaute Haugenes, former Fulham manager, disclosed that female players were safeguarded from the club’s late owner Mohamed Al Fayed due to his interest in young, blond girls. A BBC documentary unveiled multiple allegations of assault and rape against Fayed by ex-Harrods employees. Fulham is currently investigating if any staff members were affected.

item.title: China's 'beautiful governor' infamous for having multiple affairs with subordinates, arrested
item.description: Zhong Yang, ex-governor of Qiannan prefecture in Guizhou province, was sentenced to 13 years in prison and fined one million Yuan for misconduct. She accepted nearly 60 million yuan in bribes and engaged in inappropriate relationships with 58 subordinates. Zhong has been expelled from the Communist Party and stripped of her roles.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'She's very busy,' says Harris' advisor as MAGA accuses her of avoiding interviews
item.description: Keisha Lance Bottoms, senior adviser to Kamala Harris, explained that Harris's limited media engagement is due to her busy schedule as vice president and presidential candidate. Despite criticism from Donald Trump, Harris has conducted multiple interviews and addressed significant issues like reproductive freedom in various formats.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Airplane makes emergency landing after passenger finds live-mouse in meal
item.description: A Scandinavian Airlines flight traveling from Oslo to Málaga was diverted to Copenhagen after a passenger found a live mouse in his meal. Following safety protocols, the pilot made an emergency landing due to the potential hazard of rodents on board. Passengers were later transferred to another flight, resulting in only a minor delay.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: South Korea arrests trainee doctor over 'blacklist' of non-striking colleagues
item.description: A South Korean doctor was arrested for allegedly making and sharing a blacklist of colleagues who did not join the ongoing walkout over medical training reforms. The strike has severely disrupted healthcare services. The government plans to increase medical school admissions to address doctor shortages, but doctors argue it will lower service quality.

item.title: Robert F Kennedy Jr's wife furious over his alleged sexting scandal: Report
item.description: Cheryl Hines is reportedly fuming over her husband Robert F Kennedy Jr's alleged sexting scandal with reporter Olivia Nuzzi, which began during his presidential campaign. New York Magazine placed Nuzzi on leave for violating conflict of interest standards. The Kennedy family has distanced themselves from Robert, raising doubts about the couple's future.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: US elections: Let’s not pay too much attention to the polls, says Kamala Harris
item.description: At a rally in Wisconsin, vice president Kamala Harris urged supporters to focus on hard work rather than polls, identifying herself as an underdog. She emphasized unity and community-building in her campaign. With 46 days until the election, Harris holds a narrow lead over Trump nationally and in the key battleground state of Wisconsin.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Top Hezbollah commander Ahmed Wahbi killed in Israeli strike
item.description: Hezbollah reported that its top commander Ahmed Wahbi was killed in an Israeli airstrike on Beirut suburbs. The strike also took out Ibrahim Aqil, head of Hezbollah's Radwan unit. In retaliation, Hezbollah fired rockets into northern Israel. This escalation follows Hamas's attack on October 7 and has now reached Lebanon.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Who is Phillip Mehrtens? The New Zealand pilot freed after 18 months in captivity in Indonesia
item.description: New Zealand pilot Phillip Mehrtens has been released after more than 18 months of captivity by an armed faction in Indonesia's Papua region. Abducted in February 2023 while flying for Susi Air, Mehrtens is now safe and undergoing medical evaluations. The New Zealand Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade confirmed his release, facilitated by collaborative efforts with Indonesian authorities.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Watch: Woman steals Porsche, runs over owner in Toronto
item.description: A woman reportedly stole a Porsche Cayenne and ran over its owner in Toronto. Video footage shows her expressing interest in buying the car before reversing it into the victim. She fled with an accomplice in a gray Bentley Bentayga. Authorities are seeking public assistance to identify her.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Who was Freddie Owens? South Carolina inmate executed by first lethal injection in 13 years
item.description: Freddie Owens was executed by lethal injection in South Carolina's first execution in 13 years. Sentenced to death for a 1997 murder during a robbery, Owens faced multiple legal challenges up to his final moments. The case brings attention to debates over capital punishment methods and legal processes.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Elon Musk's X names legal representative in Brazil amid ban woes
item.description: Elon Musk's social media platform, X, has named Rachel de Oliveira Conceicao as its legal representative in Brazil to meet Supreme Court requirements. The appointment follows a suspension due to non-compliance with content moderation and local representation laws. The company is now adhering to court-ordered content removal directives.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Who was Ibrahim Aqil? Senior Hezbollah military commander killed in Israeli airstrike
item.description: Ibrahim Aqil, a senior Hezbollah commander and head of the elite Radwan forces, was killed in an Israeli airstrike on Beirut’s southern suburbs. The strike targeted a residential building in the Dahiyeh area, resulting in seven deaths and significant damage to Hezbollah. Aqil was reportedly planning an assault on Israeli territory. Hezbollah has not officially confirmed his death.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Trump shares fake photo of Kamala Harris with Diddy, quickly deletes it
item.description: Donald Trump shared a doctored image of Vice President Kamala Harris with rapper Sean "Diddy" Combs on Truth Social, which he later deleted after backlash. The original photo featured Harris with Montel Williams. This incident highlights ongoing misinformation against Harris, especially amid Combs' legal troubles. Montel Williams criticized the misleading post.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Lessons learned...': Secret Service admits 'mission failures' after Trump assassination attempt
item.description: The Secret Service admitted to communication failures and operational lapses during a shooting incident at Donald Trump's rally in Butler, Pennsylvania. Acting director Ronald Rowe Jr stressed the importance of accountability and improving security measures. Disciplinary actions are being considered for involved personnel, with plans to expand the security perimeter to prevent future incidents.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Crumbs the chonky cat gets stuck again, this time trying to escape 'fat camp'
item.description: Kroshik, a chubby Russian cat called 'Crumbs,' made headlines after failing to escape his weight-loss camp. Weighing 17 kg due to an unusual diet, he was rescued from a hospital basement and now stays at Perm's Matroskin Shelter. The shelter aims to bring his weight down to 4.5 kg through diet and exercise.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Election countdown: Early voting begins for the US presidential race
item.description: In-person voting for the presidential election has commenced in Minnesota, South Dakota, and Virginia. This marks the beginning of a crucial six-week period leading up to Election Day. Following a politically turbulent summer, Vice President Kamala Harris is now the Democratic nominee. Enhanced security measures are being implemented nationwide to protect polling sites and workers.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Cat goes missing, travels 800 miles to reunite with owners
item.description: Rayne Beau, a lost cat, managed to travel 800 miles back home after vanishing during a camping trip in Yellowstone National Park. Found exhausted in Roseville, California, he was reunited with his owners through his microchip. This incident emphasizes the vital role of pet microchips in reuniting lost pets with their families.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk
